stemic with deterritorializing global processes. Exploring these processes in different concrete locations from North America to Russia, West Africa, and Australia, the authors show that current configurations of global, imperial, and state power cannot be understood without examining their relation to formations of oligarchic control. They bring us closer to an understanding of the ways in which the nation-state is being transformed by globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGlobalization. 0aOligarchy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh  aTheory and Methodology.1 aIfeka, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKapferer, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNonini, Donald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReyna, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigi, Jakob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745859940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857458599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857458599/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK